# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-time-sync
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In serial communication, clock synchronization can refer to clock recovery, which achieves frequency synchronization, as opposed to full phase synchronization.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Such clock synchronization is used in synchronization in telecommunications and automatic baud rate detection.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Plesiochronous or isochronous operation refers to a system with frequency synchronization and loose constraints on phase synchronization.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Synchronous operation implies a tighter synchronization based on time perhaps in addition to frequency.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] As a result of the difficulties managing time at smaller scales, there are problems associated with clock skew that take on more complexity in distributed computing in which several computers will need to realize the same global time.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] For instance, in Unix systems, the *make* command is used to compile new or modified code and seeks to avoid recompiling unchanged code.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The *make* command uses the clock of the machine it runs on to determine which source files need to be recompiled.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] If the sources reside on a separate file server and the two machines have unsynchronized clocks, the *make* program might not produce the correct results.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is required for accurate reproduction of streaming media.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Clock synchronization is a significant component of audio over Ethernet systems.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In a system with a central server, the synchronization solution is trivial; the server will dictate the system time.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm and the Berkeley algorithm are potential solutions to the clock synchronization problem in this environment.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In distributed computing, the problem takes on more complexity because a global time is not easily known.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The most used clock synchronization solution on the Internet is the Network Time Protocol (NTP), which is a layered client-server architecture based on User Datagram Protocol (UDP) message passing.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Lamport timestamps and vector clocks are concepts of the logical clock in distributed computing.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In a wireless network, the problem becomes even more challenging due to the possibility of collision of the synchronization packets on the wireless medium and the higher drift rate of clocks on low-cost wireless devices.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The Berkeley algorithm is suitable for systems where a radio clock is not present.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] This system has no way of making sure of the actual time other than by maintaining a global average time as the global time.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] A time server will periodically fetch the time from all the time clients, average the results, and then report back to the clients the adjustment that needs be made to their local clocks to achieve the average.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] This algorithm highlights the fact that internal clocks may vary not only in the time they contain but also in the clock rate.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Clock-sampling mutual network synchronization (CS-MNS) is suitable for distributed and mobile applications.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] It has been shown to be scalable over mesh networks that include indirectly-linked non-adjacent nodes and is compatible with IEEE 802.11 and similar standards.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] It can be accurate to the order of a few microseconds but requires direct physical wireless connectivity with negligible link delay (less than 1 microsecond) on links between adjacent nodes, limiting the distance between neighboring nodes to a few hundred meters.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Cristian's algorithm relies on the existence of a time server.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The time server maintains its clock by using a radio clock or other accurate time source, then all other computers in the system stay synchronized with it.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] A time client will maintain its clock by making a procedure call to the time server.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Variations of this algorithm make more precise time calculations by factoring in network radio propagation time.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In addition to its use in navigation, the Global Positioning System (GPS) can also be used for clock synchronization.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The accuracy of GPS time signals is ±10 nanoseconds.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Using GPS (or other satellite navigation systems) for synchronization requires a receiver connected to an antenna with unobstructed view of the sky.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] IRIG timecodes are standard formats for transferring timing information.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Atomic frequency standards and GPS receivers designed for precision timing are often equipped with an IRIG output.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The standards were created by the Telecommunications Working Group of the United States military's Inter-Range Instrumentation Group (IRIG), the standards body of the Range Commanders Council.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Work on these standards started in October 1956, and the original standards were accepted in 1960.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Network Time Protocol (NTP) is a highly robust protocol, widely deployed throughout the Internet.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Well tested over the years, it is generally regarded as the state of the art in distributed time synchronization protocols for unreliable networks.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] It can reduce synchronization offsets to times of the order of a few milliseconds over the public Internet and to sub-millisecond levels over local area networks.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] A simplified version of the NTP protocol, Simple Network Time Protocol (SNTP), can also be used as a pure single-shot stateless primary/secondary synchronization protocol, but lacks the sophisticated features of NTP, and thus has much lower performance and reliability levels.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Precision Time Protocol (PTP) is a master/slave protocol for delivery of highly accurate time over local area networks.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Time Synchronization (RBS) algorithm is often used in wireless networks and sensor networks.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] In this scheme, an initiator broadcasts a reference message to urge the receivers to adjust their clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The Reference Broadcast Infrastructure Synchronization (RBIS) protocol is a master/slave synchronization protocol, like RBS, based on a receiver/receiver synchronization paradigm.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] It is specifically tailored to be used in IEEE 802.11 wireless networks configured in infrastructure mode (i.e., coordinated by an access point).
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The protocol does not require any modification to the access point.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Synchronous Ethernet uses Ethernet in a synchronous manner such that when combined with synchronization protocols such as PTP in the case of the White Rabbit Project, sub-nanosecond synchronization accuracy is achieved.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Synchronization is achieved in wireless ad hoc networks through sending synchronization messages in a multi-hop manner and each node progressively synchronizing with the node that is the immediate sender of a synchronization message.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Examples include Flooding Time Synchronization Protocol (FTSP), and Harmonia, both able to achieve synchronization with accuracy on the order of microseconds.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Researchers from Stanford and Google introduced Huygens, a probe-based, end-to-end clock synchronization algorithm.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] Huygens is implemented in software and thus can be deployed in data centers or in public cloud environments.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] By leveraging some key aspects of modern data centers and applying novel estimation algorithms and signal processing techniques, the Huygens algorithm achieved an accuracy of tens of nanoseconds even at high network load.
[src:network-time-sync/clock-synchronization] The findings of this research are being tested in financial market applications.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] officer operates the Global Positioning System in 2022.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The **Global Positioning System** (**GPS**) is a satellite-based hyperbolic navigation system owned by the United States Space Force and operated by Mission Delta 31.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It is one of the global navigation satellite systems (GNSS) that provide geolocation and time information to a GPS receiver anywhere on or near the Earth where signal quality permits.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It does not require the user to transmit any data, and operates independently of any telephone or Internet reception, though these technologies can enhance the usefulness of the GPS positioning information.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It provides critical positioning capabilities to military, civil, and commercial users around the world.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Although the United States government created, controls, and maintains GPS, it is freely accessible to anyone with a GPS receiver.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The prototype spacecraft was launched in 1978 and the full constellation of 24 satellites became operational in 1993.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As civilian GPS usage grew, there was increasing pressure to remove this error.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The SA system was temporarily disabled during the Gulf War, as a shortage of military GPS units meant that many US soldiers were using civilian GPS units sent from home.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In the 1990s, differential GPS systems from the US Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, and similar agencies in other countries began to broadcast local GPS corrections, reducing the effect of both SA degradation and atmospheric effects (that military receivers also corrected for).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The U.S. military had also developed methods to perform local GPS jamming, meaning that the ability to globally degrade the system was no longer necessary.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As a result, United States President Bill Clinton signed a bill ordering that Selective Availability be disabled on May 1, 2000; and, in 2007, the US government announced that the next generation of GPS satellites would not include the feature.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Advances in technology and new demands on the existing system have led to efforts to modernize GPS and implement the next generation of GPS Block III satellites and Next Generation Operational Control System (OCX) which was authorized by the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] When Selective Availability was discontinued, GPS was accurate to about 5 meters (16 ft).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS receivers that use the L5 band have much higher accuracy of 30 centimeters (12 in), while those for high-end applications such as engineering and land surveying are accurate to within 2 cm (3⁄4 in) and can even provide sub-millimeter accuracy with long-term measurements.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Consumer devices such as smartphones can be accurate to 4.9 m (16 ft) or better when used with assistive services like Wi-Fi positioning.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As of March 2026, 21 GPS satellites broadcast L5 signals, which are considered pre-operational prior to being broadcast by a full complement of 24 satellites in 2027.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS project was launched in the United States in 1973 to overcome the limitations of previous navigation systems, combining ideas from several predecessors, including classified engineering design studies from the 1960s.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Department of Defense developed the system, which originally used 24 satellites, for use by the United States military, and became fully operational in 1993.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Civilian use was allowed from the 1980s.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Easton of the Naval Research Laboratory, Ivan A.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Getting of The Aerospace Corporation, and Bradford Parkinson of the Applied Physics Laboratory are credited with inventing it.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The work of Gladys West of the Ballistic Sciences Branch at Dahlgren Naval Proving Ground on the creation of the mathematical geodetic Earth model is credited as instrumental in the development of computational techniques for detecting satellite positions with the precision needed for GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The design of GPS is based partly on similar ground-based radio-navigation systems, such as LORAN and the Decca Navigator System, developed in the early 1940s.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In 1955, Friedwardt Winterberg proposed a test of general relativity—detecting time slowing in a strong gravitational field using accurate atomic clocks placed in orbit inside artificial satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Special and general relativity predicted that the clocks on GPS satellites, as observed by those on Earth, run 38 microseconds faster per day than those on the Earth.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The design of GPS corrects for this difference.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] When the Soviet Union launched its first artificial satellite (Sputnik 1) in 1957, two American physicists, William Guier and George Weiffenbach, at Johns Hopkins University's Applied Physics Laboratory (APL) monitored its radio transmissions.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Within hours they realized that, because of the Doppler effect, they could pinpoint where the satellite was along its orbit.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The Director of the APL gave them access to their UNIVAC I computer to perform the heavy calculations required.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Early the next year, Frank McClure, the deputy director of the APL, asked Guier and Weiffenbach to investigate the inverse problem: pinpointing the user's location, given the satellite's.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] (At the time, the Navy was developing the submarine-launched Polaris missile, which required them to know the submarine's location.) This led them and APL to develop the TRANSIT system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In 1959, ARPA (renamed DARPA in 1972) also played a role in TRANSIT.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] TRANSIT was first successfully tested in 1960.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It used a constellation of five satellites and could provide a navigational fix approximately once per hour.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Navy developed the Timation satellite, which proved the feasibility of placing accurate clocks in space, a technology required for GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In the 1970s, the ground-based OMEGA navigation system, based on phase comparison of signal transmission from pairs of stations, became the first worldwide radio navigation system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Limitations of these systems drove the need for a more universal navigation solution with greater accuracy.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Although there were wide needs for accurate navigation in military and civilian sectors, almost none of those was seen as justification for the billions of dollars it would cost in research, development, deployment, and operation of a constellation of navigation satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] During the Cold War arms race, the nuclear threat to the existence of the United States was the one need that did justify this cost in the view of the United States Congress.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] This deterrent effect is why GPS was funded.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It is also the reason for the ultra-secrecy at that time.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The nuclear triad consisted of the United States Navy's submarine-launched ballistic missiles (SLBMs) along with United States Air Force (USAF) strategic bombers and intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Considered vital to the nuclear deterrence posture, accurate determination of the SLBM launch position was a force multiplier.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Precise navigation would enable United States ballistic missile submarines to get an accurate fix of their positions before they launched their SLBMs.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The USAF, with two-thirds of the nuclear triad, also had requirements for a more accurate and reliable navigation system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Air Force were developing their own technologies in parallel to solve what was essentially the same problem.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] To increase the survivability of ICBMs, there was a proposal to use mobile launch platforms (comparable to the Soviet SS-24 and SS-25) and so the need to fix the launch position had similarity to the SLBM situation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In 1960, the Air Force proposed a radio-navigation system called MOSAIC (Mobile System for Accurate ICBM Control) that was essentially a 3-D LORAN System.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] A follow-on study, Project 57, was performed in 1963 and it was "in this study that the GPS concept was born".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] That same year, the concept was pursued as Project 621B, which had "many of the attributes that you now see in GPS" and promised increased accuracy for U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Updates from the Navy TRANSIT system were too slow for the high speeds of Air Force operation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The Naval Research Laboratory (NRL) continued making advances with their Timation (Time Navigation) satellites, first launched in 1967, second launched in 1969, with the third in 1974 carrying the first atomic clock into orbit and the fourth launched in 1977.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Another important predecessor to GPS came from a different branch of the United States military.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In 1964, the United States Army orbited its first Sequential Collation of Range (SECOR) satellite used for geodetic surveying.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The SECOR system included three ground-based transmitters at known locations that would send signals to the satellite transponder in orbit.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] A fourth ground-based station, at an undetermined position, could then use those signals to fix its location precisely.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The last SECOR satellite was launched in 1969.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] With these parallel developments in the 1960s, a superior system could be developed by synthesizing the best technologies from 621B, Transit, Timation, and SECOR in a multi-service program.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Satellite orbital position errors, induced by variations in the gravity field and radar refraction among others, had to be resolved.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Jury of Pan Am Aerospace Division in Florida from 1970 to 1973, used real-time data assimilation and recursive estimation to do so, reducing systematic and residual errors to a manageable level to permit accurate navigation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] During Labor Day weekend in 1973, a meeting of about twelve military officers at the Pentagon discussed the creation of a *Defense Navigation Satellite System (DNSS)*.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It was at this meeting that the real synthesis that became GPS was created.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Later that year, the DNSS program was named *Navstar.* The name *Navstar* was not an acronym, but was chosen simply as a nice-sounding word.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] With the individual satellites being associated with the name Navstar (as with the predecessors Transit and Timation), a more fully encompassing name was used to identify the constellation of Navstar satellites, *Navstar-GPS*.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Ten "Block I" prototype satellites were launched between 1978 and 1985 (an additional unit was destroyed in a launch failure).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The effect of the ionosphere on radio transmission was investigated in a geophysics laboratory of Air Force Cambridge Research Laboratory, renamed to Air Force Geophysical Research Lab (AFGRL) in 1974.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] AFGRL developed the Klobuchar model for computing ionospheric corrections to GPS location.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Of note is work done by Australian space scientist Elizabeth Essex-Cohen at AFGRL in 1974.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] She was concerned with the curving of the paths of radio waves (atmospheric refraction) traversing the ionosphere from Navstar satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The first Block II satellite was launched on February 14, 1989, and the 24th satellite was launched in 1994.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS program cost at this point, not including the cost of the user equipment but including the costs of the satellite launches, has been estimated at US$5 billion (equivalent to $11 billion in 2025).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Initially, the highest-quality signal was reserved for military use, and the signal available for civilian use was intentionally degraded, in a policy known as Selective Availability.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] President Bill Clinton signing a policy directive to turn off Selective Availability to provide the same accuracy to civilians that was afforded to the military.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Secretary of Defense, William Perry, in view of the widespread growth of differential GPS services by private industry to improve civilian accuracy.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Moreover, the U.S. military was developing technologies to deny GPS service to potential adversaries on a regional basis.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Selective Availability was removed from the GPS architecture beginning with GPS-III.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Since its deployment, the U.S. has implemented several improvements to the GPS service, including new signals for civil use and increased accuracy and integrity for all users, all the while maintaining compatibility with existing GPS equipment.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Modernization of the satellite system has been an ongoing initiative by the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Department of Defense through a series of satellite acquisitions to meet the growing needs of the military, civilians, and the commercial market.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As of early 2015, high-quality Standard Positioning Service (SPS) GPS receivers provided horizontal accuracy of better than 3.5 meters (11 ft), although many factors such as receiver and antenna quality and atmospheric issues can affect this accuracy.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS is owned and operated by the United States government as a national resource.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The Department of Defense is the steward of GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The *Interagency GPS Executive Board (IGEB)* oversaw GPS policy matters from 1996 to 2004.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] After that, the National Space-Based Positioning, Navigation and Timing Executive Committee was established by presidential directive in 2004 to advise and coordinate federal departments and agencies on matters concerning the GPS and related systems.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The executive committee is chaired jointly by the Deputy Secretaries of Defense and Transportation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Its membership includes equivalent-level officials from the Departments of State, Commerce, and Homeland Security, the Joint Chiefs of Staff and NASA.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Components of the executive office of the president participate as observers to the executive committee, and the FCC chairman participates as a liaison.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] On February 10, 1993, the National Aeronautic Association selected the GPS Team as winners of the 1992 Robert J.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Collier Trophy, the US's most prestigious aviation award.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] This team combines researchers from the Naval Research Laboratory, the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Air Force, the Aerospace Corporation, Rockwell International Corporation, and IBM Federal Systems Company.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The citation honors them "for the most significant development for safe and efficient navigation and surveillance of air and spacecraft since the introduction of radio navigation 50 years ago".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Easton received the National Medal of Technology on February 13, 2006.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame at Lackland A.F.B., San Antonio, Texas, March 2, 2010, for his role in space technology development and the engineering design concept of GPS conducted as part of Project 621B.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In 1998, GPS technology was inducted into the Space Foundation Space Technology Hall of Fame.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] On October 4, 2011, the International Astronautical Federation (IAF) awarded the Global Positioning System (GPS) its 60th Anniversary Award, nominated by IAF member, the American Institute for Aeronautics and Astronautics (AIAA).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The IAF Honors and Awards Committee recognized the uniqueness of the GPS program and the exemplary role it has played in building international collaboration for the benefit of humanity.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] On December 6, 2018, Gladys West was inducted into the Air Force Space and Missile Pioneers Hall of Fame in recognition of her work on an extremely accurate geodetic Earth model, which was ultimately used to determine the orbit of the GPS constellation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS satellites carry very stable atomic clocks that are synchronized with one another and with the reference atomic clocks at the ground control stations; any drift of the clocks aboard the satellites from the reference time maintained on the ground stations is corrected regularly.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Since the speed of radio waves (speed of light) is constant and independent of the satellite speed, the time delay between when the satellite transmits a signal and the ground station receives it is proportional to the distance from the satellite to the ground station.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] With the distance information collected from multiple ground stations, the location coordinates of any satellite at any time can be calculated with great precision.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Each GPS satellite carries an accurate record of its own position and time, and broadcasts that data continuously.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Conceptually, the receiver measures the TOAs (according to its own clock) of four satellite signals.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] From the TOAs and the TOTs, the receiver forms four time of flight (TOF) values, which are (given the speed of light) approximately equivalent to receiver-satellite ranges plus time difference between the receiver and GPS satellites multiplied by speed of light, which are called pseudo-ranges.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The receiver then computes its three-dimensional position and clock deviation from the four TOFs.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In practice the receiver position (in three dimensional Cartesian coordinates with origin at the Earth's center) and the offset of the receiver clock relative to the GPS time are computed simultaneously, using the navigation equations to process the TOFs.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The receiver's Earth-centered solution location is usually converted to latitude, longitude and height relative to an ellipsoidal Earth model.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The height may then be further converted to height relative to the geoid, which is essentially mean sea level.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] These coordinates may be displayed, such as on a moving map display, or recorded or used by some other system, such as a vehicle guidance system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As of 2025, these core principles are being enhanced by the ongoing modernization of the GPS constellation with the introduction of GPS III and GPS IIIF satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] These next-generation satellites feature more advanced atomic clocks for even greater timekeeping accuracy and broadcast more powerful, secure, and interoperable signals (such as L1C, L2C, and L5).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] This improves the precision of the time-of-flight (TOF) measurements and provides better resistance to signal interference, enhancing the reliability of the position calculation for all users.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Although usually not formed explicitly in the receiver processing, the conceptual time differences of arrival (TDOAs) define the measurement geometry.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Each TDOA corresponds to a hyperboloid of revolution (see Multilateration).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The line connecting the two satellites involved (and its extensions) forms the axis of the hyperboloid.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The receiver is located at the point where three hyperboloids intersect.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It is sometimes incorrectly said that the user location is at the intersection of three spheres.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] While simpler to visualize, this is the case only if the receiver has a clock synchronized with the satellite clocks (i.e., the receiver measures true ranges to the satellites rather than range differences).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] There are marked performance benefits to the user carrying a clock synchronized with the satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Foremost is that only three satellites are needed to compute a position solution.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] If it were an essential part of the GPS concept that all users needed to carry a synchronized clock, a smaller number of satellites could be deployed, but the cost and complexity of the user equipment would increase.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The description above is representative of a receiver start-up situation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Most receivers have a track algorithm, sometimes called a *tracker*, that combines sets of satellite measurements collected at different times—in effect, taking advantage of the fact that successive receiver positions are usually close to each other.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] After a set of measurements is processed, the tracker predicts the receiver location corresponding to the next set of satellite measurements.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] When the new measurements are collected, the receiver uses a weighting scheme to combine the new measurements with the tracker prediction.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In general, a tracker can (a) improve receiver position and time accuracy, (b) reject bad measurements, and (c) estimate receiver speed and direction.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The disadvantage of a tracker is that changes in speed or direction can be computed only with a delay, and that derived direction becomes inaccurate when the distance traveled between two position measurements drops below or near the random error of position measurement.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS units can use measurements of the Doppler shift of the signals received to compute velocity accurately.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] More advanced navigation systems use additional sensors like a compass or an inertial navigation system to complement GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS requires four or more satellites to be visible for accurate navigation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The solution of the navigation equations gives the position of the receiver along with the difference between the time kept by the receiver's on-board clock and the true time-of-day, thereby eliminating the need for a more precise and possibly impractical receiver based clock.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Applications for GPS such as time transfer, traffic signal timing, and synchronization of cell phone base stations, make use of this cheap and highly accurate timing.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Some GPS applications use this time for display, or, other than for the basic position calculations, do not use it at all.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Although four satellites are required for normal operation, fewer apply in special cases.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] If one variable is already known, a receiver can determine its position using only three satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] For example, a ship on the open ocean usually has a known elevation close to 0 m, and the elevation of an aircraft may be known.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Some GPS receivers may use additional clues or assumptions such as reusing the last known altitude, dead reckoning, inertial navigation, or including information from the vehicle computer, to give a (possibly degraded) position when fewer than four satellites are visible.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The current GPS consists of three major segments.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] These are the space segment, a control segment, and a user segment.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Space Force develops, maintains, and operates the space and control segments.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS satellites broadcast signals from space, and each GPS receiver uses these signals to calculate its three-dimensional location (latitude, longitude, and altitude) and the current time.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The space segment (SS) is composed of 24 to 32 satellites, or Space Vehicles (SV), in medium Earth orbit, and also includes the payload adapters to the boosters required to launch them into orbit.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS design originally called for 24 SVs, eight each in three approximately circular orbits, but this was modified to six orbital planes with four satellites each.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The six orbit planes have approximately 55° inclination (tilt relative to the Earth's equator) and are separated by 60° right ascension of the ascending node (angle along the equator from a reference point to the orbit's intersection).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The orbital period is one-half of a sidereal day, about 11 hours and 58 minutes, so that the satellites pass over the same locations or almost the same locations every day.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The orbits are arranged so that at least six satellites are always within line of sight from everywhere on the Earth's surface (see animation at right).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The result of this objective is that the four satellites are not evenly spaced (90°) apart within each orbit.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In general terms, the angular difference between satellites in each orbit is 30°, 105°, 120°, and 105° apart, which sum to 360°.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Orbiting at an altitude of approximately 20,200 km (12,600 mi); orbital radius of approximately 26,600 km (16,500 mi), each SV makes two complete orbits each sidereal day, repeating the same ground track each day.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] This was very helpful during development because even with only four satellites, correct alignment means all four are visible from one spot for a few hours each day.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] For military operations, the ground track repeat can be used to ensure good coverage in combat zones.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As of February 2019, there are 31 satellites in the GPS constellation, 27 of which are in use at a given time with the rest allocated as stand-bys.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] A 32nd was launched in 2018, but as of July 2019 is still in evaluation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] More decommissioned satellites are in orbit and available as spares.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The additional satellites improve the precision of GPS receiver calculations by providing redundant measurements.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] With the increased number of satellites, the constellation was changed to a nonuniform arrangement.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Such an arrangement was shown to improve accuracy but also improves reliability and availability of the system, relative to a uniform system, when multiple satellites fail.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] With the expanded constellation, nine satellites are usually visible at any time from any point on the Earth with a clear horizon, ensuring considerable redundancy over the minimum four satellites needed for a position.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The MCS can also access Satellite Control Network (SCN) ground antennas (for additional command and control capability) and NGA (National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency) monitor stations.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The flight paths of the satellites are tracked by dedicated U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Space Force monitoring stations in Hawaii, Kwajalein Atoll, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, Colorado Springs, Colorado and Cape Canaveral, Florida, along with shared NGA monitor stations operated in England, Argentina, Ecuador, Bahrain, Australia and Washington, DC.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The tracking information is sent to the MCS at Schriever Space Force Base 25 km (16 mi) ESE of Colorado Springs, which is operated by the 2nd Space Operations Squadron (2 SOPS) of the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Then 2 SOPS contacts each GPS satellite regularly with a navigational update using dedicated or shared (AFSCN) ground antennas (GPS dedicated ground antennas are located at Kwajalein, Ascension Island, Diego Garcia, and Cape Canaveral).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] These updates synchronize the atomic clocks on board the satellites to within a few nanoseconds of each other, and adjust the ephemeris of each satellite's internal orbital model.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The updates are created by a Kalman filter that uses inputs from the ground monitoring stations, space weather information, and various other inputs.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] When a satellite's orbit is being adjusted, the satellite is marked *unhealthy*, so receivers do not use it.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] After the maneuver, engineers track the new orbit from the ground, upload the new ephemeris, and mark the satellite healthy again.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The operation control segment (OCS) currently serves as the control segment of record.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It provides the operational capability that supports GPS users and keeps the GPS operational and performing within specification.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] OCS replaced the 1970s-era mainframe computer at Schriever Air Force Base in September 2007.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] After installation, the system helped enable upgrades and provide a foundation for a new security architecture that supported U.S. armed forces.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] OCS will continue to be the ground control system of record until the new segment, Next Generation GPS Operation Control System (OCX), is fully developed and functional.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Department of Defense has claimed that the new capabilities provided by OCX will be the cornerstone for enhancing GPS's mission capabilities, enabling U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Space Force to enhance GPS operational services to U.S. combat forces, civil partners and domestic and international users.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS OCX program also will reduce cost, schedule and technical risk.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] It is designed to provide 50% sustainment cost savings through efficient software architecture and Performance-Based Logistics.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In addition, GPS OCX is expected to cost millions of dollars less than the cost to upgrade OCS while providing four times the capability.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS OCX program represents a critical part of GPS modernization and provides information assurance improvements over the current GPS OCS program.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Air Force announced the completion of GPS OCX Preliminary Design Review and confirmed that the OCX program is ready for the next phase of development.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The GPS OCX program missed major milestones and pushed its launch into 2021, 5 years past the original deadline.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] According to the Government Accounting Office in 2019, the 2021 deadline looked shaky.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The project remained delayed in 2023, and was (as of June 2023) 73% over its original estimated budget.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In late 2023, Frank Calvelli, the assistant secretary of the Air Force for space acquisitions and integration, stated that the project was estimated to go live some time during the summer of 2024.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The US Space Force accepted delivery of OCX Blocks I and II from contractor RTX on July 1, 2025, over 8 years behind schedule and roughly $4 billion over budget due to its monolithic development and constant feature creep while in process.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] If current Government Accountability Office estimates hold, the new system will enter service in December 2025.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] OCX Block 3F is currently in development to enable command and control of GPS IIIF satellites, currently slated to begin launching in 2027.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] The user segment (US) is composed of hundreds of thousands of U.S. and allied military users of the secure GPS Precise Positioning Service, and tens of millions of civil, commercial and scientific users of the Standard Positioning Service.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] In general, GPS receivers are composed of an antenna, tuned to the frequencies transmitted by the satellites, receiver-processors, and a highly stable clock (often a crystal oscillator).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] They may also include a display for providing location and speed information to the user.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] GPS receivers may include an input for differential corrections, using the RTCM SC-104 format.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] This is typically in the form of an RS-232 port at 4,800 bit/s speed.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Data is actually sent at a much lower rate, which limits the accuracy of the signal sent using RTCM.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Receivers with internal DGPS receivers can outperform those using external RTCM data.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] As of 2006, even low-cost units commonly include Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS) receivers.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Many GPS receivers can relay position data to a PC or other device using the NMEA 0183 protocol.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Although this protocol is officially defined by the National Marine Electronics Association (NMEA), references to this protocol have been compiled from public records, allowing open source tools like gpsd to read the protocol without violating intellectual property laws.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Other proprietary protocols exist as well, such as the SiRF and MTK protocols.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p01] Receivers can interface with other devices using methods including a serial connection, USB, or Bluetooth.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] While originally a military project, GPS is considered a dual-use technology, meaning it has significant civilian applications as well.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS has become a widely deployed and useful tool for commerce, scientific uses, tracking, and surveillance.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS's accurate time facilitates everyday activities such as banking, mobile phone operations, and even the control of power grids by allowing well synchronized hand-off switching.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Many civilian applications use one or more of GPS's three basic components: absolute location, relative movement, and time transfer.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The U.S. government controls the export of some civilian receivers.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This rule applies even to otherwise purely civilian units that only receive the L1 frequency and the C/A (Coarse/Acquisition) code.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Disabling operation above these limits exempts the receiver from classification as a munition.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The rule refers to operation at both the target altitude and speed, but some receivers stop operating even when stationary.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This has caused problems with some amateur radio balloon launches that regularly reach 30 km (100,000 ft).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] These limits only apply to units or components exported from the United States.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] A growing trade in various components exists, including GPS units from other countries.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS type navigation was first used in war in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, before GPS was fully developed in 1995, to assist Coalition Forces to navigate and perform maneuvers in the war.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The war also demonstrated the vulnerability of GPS to being jammed, when Iraqi forces installed jamming devices on likely targets that emitted radio noise, disrupting reception of the weak GPS signal.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS's vulnerability to jamming is a threat that continues to grow as jamming equipment and experience grows.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS signals have been reported to have been jammed many times over the years for military purposes.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Russia seems to have several objectives for this approach, such as intimidating neighbors while undermining confidence in their reliance on American systems, promoting their GLONASS alternative, disrupting Western military exercises, and protecting assets from drones.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] China uses jamming to discourage US surveillance aircraft near the contested Spratly Islands.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] North Korea has mounted several major jamming operations near its border with South Korea and offshore, disrupting flights, shipping and fishing operations.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Iranian Armed Forces disrupted the civilian airliner plane Flight PS752's GPS when it shot down the aircraft.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In the Russo-Ukrainian War, GPS-guided munitions provided to Ukraine by NATO countries experienced significant failure rates as a result of Russian electronic warfare.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Excalibur artillery shells efficiency rate hitting targets dropped from 70% to 6% as Russia adapted its electronic warfare activities.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] While most clocks derive their time from Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), the atomic clocks on the satellites are set to *GPS time*.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The difference is that GPS time is not corrected to match the rotation of the Earth, so it does not contain new leap seconds or other corrections that are periodically added to UTC.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS time was set to match UTC in 1980, but has since diverged.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The lack of corrections means that GPS time remains at a constant offset with International Atomic Time (TAI) (TAI – GPS = 19 seconds).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Periodic corrections are performed to the on-board clocks to keep them synchronized with ground clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS navigation message includes the difference between GPS time and UTC.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] As of January 2017, GPS time is 18 seconds ahead of UTC because of the leap second added to UTC on December 31, 2016.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Receivers subtract this offset from GPS time to calculate UTC and specific time zone values.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] New GPS units may not show the correct UTC time until after receiving the UTC offset message.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS-UTC offset field can accommodate 255 leap seconds (eight bits).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS time is theoretically accurate to about 14 nanoseconds, due to the clock drift relative to International Atomic Time that the atomic clocks in GPS transmitters experience.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Most receivers lose some accuracy in their interpretation of the signals and are only accurate to about 100 nanoseconds.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS implements two major corrections to its time signals for relativistic effects: one for relative velocity of satellite and receiver, using the special theory of relativity, and one for the difference in gravitational potential between satellite and receiver, using general relativity.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The acceleration of the satellite could also be computed independently as a correction, depending on purpose, but normally the effect is already dealt with in the first two corrections.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] As opposed to the year, month, and day format of the Gregorian calendar, the GPS date is expressed as a week number and a seconds-into-week number.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The week number is transmitted as a ten-bit field in the C/A and P(Y) navigation messages, and so it becomes zero again every 1,024 weeks (19.6 years).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] It happened the second time at 23:59:42 UTC on April 6, 2019.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] To determine the current Gregorian date, a GPS receiver must be provided with the approximate date (to within 3,584 days) to correctly translate the GPS date signal.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] To address this concern in the future the modernized GPS civil navigation (CNAV) message uses a 13-bit field that only repeats every 8,192 weeks (157 years), thus lasting until 2137 (157 years after GPS week zero).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The navigational signals transmitted by GPS satellites encode a variety of information including satellite positions, the state of the internal clocks, and the health of the network.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] These signals are transmitted on two separate carrier frequencies that are common to all satellites in the network.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Two different encodings are used: a public encoding that enables lower resolution navigation, and an encrypted encoding used by the U.S. military.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Each GPS satellite continuously broadcasts a *navigation message* on L1 (C/A and P/Y) and L2 (P/Y) frequencies at a rate of 50 bits per second (see bitrate).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Each complete message takes 750 seconds (12+1⁄2 minutes) to complete.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The message structure has a basic format of a 1500-bit-long frame made up of five subframes, each subframe being 300 bits (6 seconds) long.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Subframes 4 and 5 are subcommutated 25 times each, so that a complete data message requires the transmission of 25 full frames.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Each subframe consists of ten words, each 30 bits long.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Thus, with 300 bits in a subframe times 5 subframes in a frame times 25 frames in a message, each message is 37,500 bits long.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] At a transmission rate of 50-bit/s, this gives 750 seconds to transmit an entire almanac message (GPS).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Each 30-second frame begins precisely on the minute or half-minute as indicated by the atomic clock on each satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The first subframe of each frame encodes the week number and the time within the week, as well as the data about the health of the satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The second and the third subframes contain the *ephemeris* – the precise orbital parameters for the satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The fourth and fifth subframes contain the *almanac*, which contains coarse orbit and status information for up to 32 satellites in the constellation as well as data related to error correction.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Thus, to obtain an accurate satellite location from this transmitted message, the receiver must demodulate the message from each satellite it includes in its solution for 18 to 30 seconds.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] To collect all transmitted almanacs, the receiver must demodulate the message for 732 to 750 seconds or 12+1⁄2 minutes.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same frequencies, encoding signals using unique code-division multiple access (CDMA) so receivers can distinguish individual satellites from each other.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The system uses two distinct CDMA encoding types: the coarse/acquisition (C/A) code, which is accessible by the general public, and the precise (P(Y)) code, which is encrypted so that only the U.S. military and other NATO nations who have been given access to the encryption code can access it.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The ephemeris is updated every 2 hours and is sufficiently stable for 4 hours, with provisions for updates every 6 hours or longer in non-nominal conditions.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The almanac is updated typically every 24 hours.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Additionally, data for a few weeks following is uploaded in case of transmission updates that delay data upload.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] All satellites broadcast at the same two frequencies, 1.57542 GHz (L1 signal) and 1.2276 GHz (L2 signal).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The satellite network uses a CDMA spread-spectrum technique where the low-bitrate message data is encoded with a high-rate pseudo-random (PRN) sequence that is different for each satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver must be aware of the PRN codes for each satellite to reconstruct the actual message data.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The C/A code, for civilian use, transmits data at 1.023 million chips per second, whereas the P code, for U.S. military use, transmits at 10.23 million chips per second.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The actual internal reference of the satellites is 10.22999999543 MHz to compensate for relativistic effects that make observers on the Earth perceive a different time reference with respect to the transmitters in orbit.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The L1 carrier is modulated by both the C/A and P codes, while the L2 carrier is only modulated by the P code.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The P code can be encrypted as a so-called P(Y) code that is only available to military equipment with a proper decryption key.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Both the C/A and P(Y) codes impart the precise time-of-day to the user.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The L3 signal at a frequency of 1.38105 GHz is used to transmit data from the satellites to ground stations.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This data is used by the United States Nuclear Detonation (NUDET) Detection System (USNDS) to detect, locate, and report nuclear detonations (NUDETs) in the Earth's atmosphere and near space.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] One usage is the enforcement of nuclear test ban treaties.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The L4 band at 1.379913 GHz is being studied for additional ionospheric correction.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The L5 frequency band at 1.17645 GHz was added in the process of GPS modernization.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This frequency falls into an internationally protected range for aeronautical navigation, promising little or no interference under all circumstances.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The first Block IIF satellite that provides this signal was launched in May 2010.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] On February 5, 2016, the 12th and final Block IIF satellite was launched.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The L5 consists of two carrier components that are in phase quadrature with each other.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Each carrier component is bi-phase shift key (BPSK) modulated by a separate bit train.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In 2011, a conditional waiver was granted to LightSquared to operate a terrestrial broadband service near the L1 band.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS community had not objected to the LightSquared (formerly MSV and SkyTerra) applications until November 2010, when LightSquared applied for a modification to its Ancillary Terrestrial Component (ATC) authorization.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This filing (SAT-MOD-20101118-00239) amounted to a request to run several orders of magnitude more power in the same frequency band for terrestrial base stations, essentially repurposing what was supposed to be a "quiet neighborhood" for signals from space as the equivalent of a cellular network.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Testing in the first half of 2011 has demonstrated that the effects from the lower 10 MHz of spectrum are minimal to GPS devices (less than 1% of the total GPS devices are affected).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The upper 10 MHz intended for use by LightSquared may have some effect on GPS devices.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] There is some concern that this may seriously degrade the GPS signal for many consumer uses.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] *Aviation Week* magazine reports that the latest testing (June 2011) confirms "significant jamming" of GPS by LightSquared's system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Because all of the satellite signals are modulated onto the same L1 carrier frequency, the signals must be separated after demodulation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This is done by assigning each satellite a unique binary sequence known as a Gold code.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The signals are decoded after demodulation using addition of the Gold codes corresponding to the satellites monitored by the receiver.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] If the almanac information has previously been acquired, the receiver picks the satellites to listen for by their PRNs, unique numbers in the range 1 through 32.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] If the almanac information is not in memory, the receiver enters a search mode until a lock is obtained on one of the satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] To obtain a lock, it is necessary that there be an unobstructed line of sight from the receiver to the satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver can then acquire the almanac and determine the satellites it should listen for.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] As it detects each satellite's signal, it identifies it by its distinct C/A code pattern.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] There can be a delay of up to 30 seconds before the first estimate of position because of the need to read the ephemeris data.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Processing of the navigation message enables the determination of the time of transmission and the satellite position at this time.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] For more information see Demodulation and Decoding, Advanced.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver uses messages received from satellites to determine the satellite positions and time sent.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The *x, y,* and *z* components of satellite position and the time sent (*s*) are designated as [*xi, yi, zi, si*] where the subscript *i* denotes the satellite and has the value 1, 2, ..., *n*, where *n* ≥ 4.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When the time of message reception indicated by the on-board receiver clock is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}$ , the true reception time is $t_{i}={\tilde {t}}_{i}-b$ , where *b* is the receiver's clock bias from the much more accurate GPS clocks employed by the satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver clock bias is the same for all received satellite signals (assuming the satellite clocks are all perfectly synchronized).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The message's transit time is ${\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}$ , where *si* is the satellite time.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Assuming the message traveled at the speed of light, *c*, the distance traveled is $\left({\tilde {t}}_{i}-b-s_{i}\right)c$ .
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Since the equations have four unknowns [*x, y, z, b*]—the three components of GPS receiver position and the clock bias—signals from at least four satellites are necessary to attempt solving these equations.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] They can be solved by algebraic or numerical methods.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Existence and uniqueness of GPS solutions are discussed by Abell and Chaffee.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When *n* is greater than four, this system is overdetermined and a fitting method must be used.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The amount of error in the results varies with the received satellites' locations in the sky, since certain configurations (when the received satellites are close together in the sky) cause larger errors.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Receivers usually calculate a running estimate of the error in the calculated position.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This is done by multiplying the basic resolution of the receiver by quantities called the geometric dilution of position (GDOP) factors, calculated from the relative sky directions of the satellites used.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver location is expressed in a specific coordinate system, such as latitude and longitude using the WGS 84 geodetic datum or a country-specific system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS equations can be solved by numerical and analytical methods.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Geometrical interpretations can enhance the understanding of these solution methods.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The measured ranges, called pseudoranges, contain clock errors.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In a simplified idealization in which the ranges are synchronized, these true ranges represent the radii of spheres, each centered on one of the transmitting satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The solution for the position of the receiver is then at the intersection of the surfaces of these spheres; see trilateration (more generally, true-range multilateration).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Signals from at minimum three satellites are required, and their three spheres would typically intersect at two points.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] One of the points is the location of the receiver, and the other moves rapidly in successive measurements and would not usually be on Earth's surface.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In practice, there are many sources of inaccuracy besides clock bias, including random errors as well as the potential for precision loss from subtracting numbers close to each other if the centers of the spheres are relatively close together.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This means that the position calculated from three satellites alone is unlikely to be accurate enough.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Data from more satellites can help because of the tendency for random errors to cancel out and also by giving a larger spread between the sphere centers.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] But at the same time, more spheres will not generally intersect at one point.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Therefore, a near intersection gets computed, typically via least squares.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The more signals available, the better the approximation is likely to be.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] If the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *i* and the pseudorange between the receiver and satellite *j* are subtracted, *pi* − *pj*, the common receiver clock bias (*b*) cancels out, resulting in a difference of distances *di* − *dj*.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The locus of points having a constant difference in distance to two points (here, two satellites) is a hyperbola on a plane and a hyperboloid of revolution (more specifically, a two-sheeted hyperboloid) in 3D space (see Multilateration).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Thus, from four pseudorange measurements, the receiver can be placed at the intersection of the surfaces of three hyperboloids each with foci at a pair of satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] With additional satellites, the multiple intersections are not necessarily unique, and a best-fitting solution is sought instead.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver position can be interpreted as the center of an inscribed sphere (insphere) of radius *bc*, given by the receiver clock bias *b* (scaled by the speed of light *c*).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The insphere location is such that it touches other spheres.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The circumscribing spheres are centered at the GPS satellites, whose radii equal the measured pseudoranges *p*i.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This configuration is distinct from the one described above, in which the spheres' radii were the unbiased or geometric ranges *d*i.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The clock in the receiver is usually not of the same quality as the ones in the satellites and will not be accurately synchronized to them.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This produces pseudoranges with large differences compared to the true distances to the satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Therefore, in practice, the time difference between the receiver clock and the satellite time is defined as an unknown clock bias *b*.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The equations are then solved simultaneously for the receiver position and the clock bias.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The solution space [*x, y, z, b*] can be seen as a four-dimensional spacetime, and signals from at minimum four satellites are needed.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In that case each of the equations describes a hypercone (or spherical cone), with the cusp located at the satellite, and the base a sphere around the satellite.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The receiver is at the intersection of four or more of such hypercones.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When more than four satellites are available, the calculation can use the four best, or more than four simultaneously (up to all visible satellites), depending on the number of receiver channels, processing capability, and geometric dilution of precision (GDOP).
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Using more than four involves an over-determined system of equations with no unique solution; such a system can be solved by a least-squares or weighted least squares method.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Both the equations for four satellites, or the least squares equations for more than four, are non-linear and need special solution methods.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] A common approach is by iteration on a linearized form of the equations, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The GPS was initially developed assuming use of a numerical least-squares solution method—i.e., before closed-form solutions were found.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] One closed-form solution to the above set of equations was developed by S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Its properties are well known; in particular, proponents claim it is superior in low-GDOP situations, compared to iterative least squares methods.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Bancroft's method is algebraic, as opposed to numerical, and can be used for four or more satellites.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When four satellites are used, the key steps are inversion of a 4x4 matrix and solution of a single-variable quadratic equation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Bancroft's method provides one or two solutions for the unknown quantities.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When there are two (usually the case), only one is a near-Earth sensible solution.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] When a receiver uses more than four satellites for a solution, Bancroft uses the generalized inverse (i.e., the pseudoinverse) to find a solution.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] A case has been made that iterative methods, such as the Gauss–Newton algorithm approach for solving over-determined non-linear least squares problems, generally provide more accurate solutions.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] (2015) states that "Bancroft's (1985) solution is a very early, if not the first, closed-form solution." Other closed-form solutions were published afterwards, although their adoption in practice is unclear.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS error analysis examines error sources in GPS results and the expected size of those errors.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS makes corrections for receiver clock errors and other effects, but some residual errors remain uncorrected.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Error sources include signal arrival time measurements, numerical calculations, atmospheric effects (ionospheric/tropospheric delays), ephemeris and clock data, multipath signals, and natural and artificial interference.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Magnitude of residual errors from these sources depends on geometric dilution of precision.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Artificial errors may result from jamming devices and threaten ships and aircraft or from intentional signal degradation through selective availability, which limited accuracy to ≈ 6–12 m (20–40 ft), but has been switched off since May 1, 2000.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GNSS enhancement refers to techniques used to improve the accuracy of positioning information provided by the Global Positioning System or other global navigation satellite systems in general, a network of satellites used for navigation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Enhancement methods of improving accuracy rely on external information being integrated into the calculation process.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] There are many such systems in place and they are generally named or described based on how the GPS sensor receives the information.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In the United States, GPS receivers are regulated under the Federal Communications Commission's (FCC) Part 15 rules.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] As indicated in the manuals of GPS-enabled devices sold in the United States, as a Part 15 device, it "must accept any interference received, including interference that may cause undesired operation".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] With respect to GPS devices in particular, the FCC states that GPS receiver manufacturers "must use receivers that reasonably discriminate against reception of signals outside their allocated spectrum".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] For the last 30 years, GPS receivers have operated next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and have discriminated against reception of mobile satellite services, such as Inmarsat, without any issue.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The spectrum allocated for GPS L1 use by the FCC is 1559 to 1610 MHz, while the spectrum allocated for satellite-to-ground use owned by LightSquared is the Mobile Satellite Service band.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Since 1996, the FCC has authorized licensed use of the spectrum neighboring the GPS band of 1525 to 1559 MHz to the Virginia company LightSquared.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] On March 1, 2001, the FCC received an application from LightSquared's predecessor, Motient Services, to use their allocated frequencies for an integrated satellite-terrestrial service.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS Industry Council came to an out-of-band-emissions (OOBE) agreement with LightSquared to prevent transmissions from LightSquared's ground-based stations from emitting transmissions into the neighboring GPS band of 1559 to 1610 MHz.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] We do not intend, nor will we permit, the terrestrial component to become a stand-alone service." This authorization was reviewed and approved by the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Interdepartment Radio Advisory Committee, which includes the U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Coast Guard, Federal Aviation Administration, National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), U.S.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The January 2011 order makes final authorization contingent upon studies of GPS interference issues carried out by a LightSquared led working group along with GPS industry and Federal agency participation.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] On February 14, 2012, the FCC initiated proceedings to vacate LightSquared's Conditional Waiver Order based on the NTIA's conclusion that there was currently no practical way to mitigate potential GPS interference.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] GPS receiver manufacturers design GPS receivers to use spectrum beyond the GPS-allocated band.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In some cases, GPS receivers are designed to use up to 400 MHz of spectrum in either direction of the L1 frequency of 1575.42 MHz, because mobile satellite services in those regions are broadcasting from space to ground, and at power levels commensurate with mobile satellite services.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] As regulated under the FCC's Part 15 rules, GPS receivers are not warranted protection from signals outside GPS-allocated spectrum.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] This is why GPS operates next to the Mobile Satellite Service band, and also why the Mobile Satellite Service band operates next to GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The symbiotic relationship of spectrum allocation ensures that users of both bands are able to operate cooperatively and freely.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The FCC adopted rules in February 2003 that allowed Mobile Satellite Service (MSS) licensees such as LightSquared to construct a small number of ancillary ground-based towers in their licensed spectrum to "promote more efficient use of terrestrial wireless spectrum".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] MSS ATC is unlikely to compete directly with terrestrial CMRS for the same customer base...".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In 2004, the FCC clarified that the ground-based towers would be ancillary, noting: "We will authorize MSS ATC subject to conditions that ensure that the added terrestrial component remains ancillary to the principal MSS offering.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] To build public support of efforts to continue the 2004 FCC authorization of LightSquared's ancillary terrestrial component vs. a simple ground-based LTE service in the Mobile Satellite Service band, GPS receiver manufacturer Trimble Navigation Ltd. formed the "Coalition To Save Our GPS".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The FCC and LightSquared have each made public commitments to solve the GPS interference issue before the network is allowed to operate.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] According to Chris Dancy of the Aircraft Owners and Pilots Association, airline pilots with the type of systems that would be affected "may go off course and not even realize it".
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The problems could also affect the Federal Aviation Administration upgrade to the air traffic control system, United States Defense Department guidance, and local emergency services including 911.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] LightSquared is challenging the FCC's action.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] Following the United States's deployment of GPS, other countries have also developed their own satellite navigation systems.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] In the event of adverse space weather or the deployment of an anti-satellite weapon against GPS, the United States has no terrestrial backup system.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The potential cost of such an event to the U.S. economy is estimated at $1 billion per day.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] The LORAN-C system was turned off in North America in 2010 and Europe in 2015. eLoran is proposed as an American terrestrial backup system, but as of 2024 has not received approval or funding.
[src:network-time-sync/gps-p02] China continues to operate LORAN-C transmitters, and Russia has a similar system called CHAYKA ("Seagull").
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The **Network Time Protocol** (**NTP**) is a networking protocol for clock synchronization between computer systems over packet-switched, variable-latency data networks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In operation since before 1985, NTP is one of the oldest Internet protocols in current use.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP is intended to synchronize participating computers to within a few milliseconds of Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It uses the intersection algorithm, a modified version of Marzullo's algorithm, to select accurate time servers and is designed to mitigate the effects of variable network latency.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP can usually maintain time to within tens of milliseconds over the public Internet, and can achieve better than one millisecond accuracy in local area networks under ideal conditions.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Asymmetric routes and network congestion can cause errors of 100 ms or more.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The protocol is usually described in terms of a client–server model, but can as easily be used in peer-to-peer relationships where both peers consider the other to be a potential time source.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Implementations send and receive timestamps using the User Datagram Protocol (UDP); the service is normally on port number 123, and in some modes both sides use this port number.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] They can also use broadcasting or multicasting, where clients passively listen to time updates after an initial round-trip calibrating exchange.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP supplies a warning of any impending leap second adjustment, but no information about local time zones or daylight saving time is transmitted.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The current protocol is version 4 (NTPv4), which is backward compatible with version 3.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A typical NTP client regularly polls one or more NTP servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The client must compute its time offset and round-trip delay.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Time offset *θ* is the positive or negative (client time > server time) difference in absolute time between the two clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] To derive the expression for the offset, note that for the request packet, $t_{0}+\theta +\delta /2=t_{1}$ and for the response packet, $t_{3}+\theta -\delta /2=t_{2}$ Solving for *θ* yields the definition of the time offset.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The values for *θ* and *δ* are passed through filters and subjected to statistical analysis ("mitigation").
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Outliers are discarded and an estimate of time offset is derived from the best three remaining candidates.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The clock frequency is then adjusted to reduce the offset gradually ("discipline"), creating a feedback loop.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Accurate synchronization is achieved when both the incoming and outgoing routes between the client and the server have symmetrical nominal delay.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] If the routes do not have a common nominal delay, a systematic bias exists of half the difference between the forward and backward travel times.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A number of approaches have been proposed to measure asymmetry, but among practical implementations only chrony seems to have one included.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1979, network time synchronization technology was used in what was possibly the first public demonstration of Internet services running over a trans-Atlantic satellite network, at the National Computer Conference in New York.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The technology was later described in the 1981 Internet Engineering Note (IEN) 173 and a public protocol was developed from it that was documented in RFC 778.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The technology was first deployed in a local area network as part of the Hello routing protocol and implemented in the Fuzzball router, an experimental operating system used in network prototyping, where it ran for many years.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Other related network tools were available both then and now.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] They include the Daytime and Time protocols for recording the time of events, as well as the ICMP Timestamp messages and IP Timestamp option (RFC 781).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1985, NTP version 0 (NTPv0) was implemented in both Fuzzball and Unix, and the NTP packet header and round-trip delay and offset calculations, which have persisted into NTPv4, were documented in RFC 958.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Despite the relatively slow computers and networks available at the time, accuracy of better than 100 milliseconds was usually obtained on Atlantic spanning links, with accuracy of tens of milliseconds on Ethernet networks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1988, a much more complete specification of the NTPv1 protocol, with associated algorithms, was published in RFC 1059.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It drew on the experimental results and clock filter algorithm documented in RFC 956 and was the first version to describe the client–server and peer-to-peer modes.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1991, the NTPv1 architecture, protocol and algorithms were brought to the attention of a wider engineering community with the publication of an article by David L.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Mills in the *IEEE Transactions on Communications*.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1989, RFC 1119 was published defining NTPv2 by means of a state machine, with pseudocode to describe its operation.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It introduced a management protocol and cryptographic authentication scheme which have both survived into NTPv4, along with the bulk of the algorithm.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] However the design of NTPv2 was criticized for lacking formal correctness by the DTSS community, and the clock selection procedure was modified to incorporate Marzullo's algorithm for NTPv3 onwards.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The RFC included an analysis of all sources of error, from the reference clock down to the final client, which enabled the calculation of a metric that helps choose the best server where several candidates appear to disagree.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In subsequent years, as new features were added and algorithm improvements were made, it became apparent that a new protocol version was required.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 2010, RFC 5905 was published containing a proposed specification for NTPv4.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Following the retirement of Mills from the University of Delaware, the reference implementation is currently maintained as an open source project led by Harlan Stenn.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] On the IANA side, a ntp (network time *protocols*) work group is in charge of reviewing proposed drafts.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The protocol has significantly progressed since NTPv4.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] As of 2022, three RFC documents describing updates to the protocol have been published, not counting the numerous peripheral standards such as Network Time Security.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Mills had mentioned plans for a "NTPv5" on his page, but one was never published.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Lichvar of chrony was initiated in 2020 and includes security, accuracy, and scaling changes.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] As NTP replaced the old Time Protocol, some use cases nevertheless found the full protocol too complicated.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1992, **Simple Network Time Protocol** (**SNTP**) was defined to fill this niche.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The SNTPv3 standard describes a way to use NTPv3 such that no storage of state over an extended period is needed.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The topology becomes essentially the same as with the Time Protocol, as only one server is used.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 1996, SNTP was updated to SNTPv4, with some features of the then-in-development NTPv4.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] SNTPv4 was merged into the main NTPv4 standard in 2010.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] SNTP is fully interoperable with NTP since it does not define a new protocol, as it utilizes the same packet format and port as NTP, ensuring compatibility with NTP servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] However, client/server will lack the complex algorithms required to filter network jitter, analyze clock drift, or cross-reference multiple time sources.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This makes it suitable for IoT devices and basic hardware that require "good enough" time without the overhead of a full NTP application stack.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] An SNTP client typically operates by querying a single server and applying the received time directly to the local clock.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] However, the simple algorithms provide times of reduced accuracy and thus it is inadvisable to sync time from an SNTP source.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] However, RFC 5905 notes that because the additional complexity of the full on-wire protocol is minimal, full implementation is encouraged even for simple clients.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP uses a hierarchical, semi-layered system of time sources.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Each level of this hierarchy is termed a *stratum* and is assigned a number starting with zero for the reference clock at the top.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A server synchronized to a stratum *n* server runs at stratum *n* + 1.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The number represents the distance from the reference clock and is used to prevent cyclical dependencies in the hierarchy.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Stratum is not always an indication of quality or reliability; it is common to find stratum 3 time sources that are higher quality than some stratum 2 time sources.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Brief descriptions of strata 0, 1, 2 and 3 are provided below.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP servers cannot advertise themselves as stratum 0; a stratum field set to 0 in an NTP message indicates an unspecified stratum.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] is synchronized to within a few microseconds of their attached stratum 0 devices.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] They are also referred to as primary time servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] These are computers that are synchronized over a network to stratum 1 servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Often a stratum 2 computer queries several stratum 1 servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Stratum 2 computers may also peer with other stratum 2 computers to provide more stable and robust time for all devices in the peer group.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] These are computers that are synchronized to stratum 2 servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] They employ the same algorithms for peering and data sampling as stratum 2, and can themselves act as servers for stratum 4 computers, and so on.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The upper limit for stratum is 15; stratum 16 is used to indicate that a device is unsynchronized.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The NTP algorithms on each computer interact to construct a Bellman–Ford shortest-path spanning tree, to minimize the accumulated round-trip delay to the stratum 1 servers for all the clients.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In addition to stratum, the protocol is able to identify the synchronization source for each server in terms of a reference identifier (refid).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] For servers on stratum 2 and below, the refid is an encoded form of the upstream time server's IP address.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] For IPv4, this is simply the 32-bit address; for IPv6, it would be the first 32 bits of the MD5 hash of the source address.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Refids serve to detect and prevent timing loops to the first degree.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The refid field is filled with status words in the case of kiss-o'-death (KoD) packets, which tell the client to stop sending requests so that the server can rest.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Some examples are INIT (initialization), STEP (step time change), and RATE (client requesting too fast).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The program output may additionally use codes not transmitted in the packet to indicate error, such as XFAC to indicate a network disconnection.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The IANA maintains a registry for refid source names and KoD codes.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The NTP reference implementation, along with the protocol, has been continuously developed for over 20 years.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Backwards compatibility has been maintained as new features have been added.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It contains several sensitive algorithms, especially to discipline the clock, that can misbehave when synchronized to servers that use different algorithms.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The software has been ported to almost every computing platform, including personal computers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It runs as a daemon called ntpd under Unix or as a service under Windows.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Reference clocks are supported and their offsets are filtered and analysed in the same way as remote servers, although they are usually polled more frequently.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This implementation was audited in 2017, finding 14 potential security issues.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] All Microsoft Windows versions since Windows 2000 include the Windows Time service (W32Time), which has the ability to synchronize the computer clock to an NTP server.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] W32Time was originally implemented for the purpose of the Kerberos version 5 authentication protocol, which required time to be within 5 minutes of the correct value to prevent replay attacks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The network time server in Windows 2000 Server (and Windows XP) does not implement NTP disciplined synchronization, only locally disciplined synchronization with NTP/SNTP correction.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Beginning with Windows Server 2003 and Windows Vista, the NTP provider for W32Time became compatible with a significant subset of NTPv3.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Microsoft states that W32Time cannot reliably maintain time synchronization with one second accuracy.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] If higher accuracy is desired, Microsoft recommends using a newer version of Windows or different NTP implementation.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Beginning with Windows 10 version 1607 and Windows Server 2016, W32Time can be configured to reach time accuracy of 1 s, 50 ms or 1 ms under certain specified operating conditions.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] In 2004, Henning Brauer of OpenBSD presented OpenNTPD, an NTPv3/SNTPv4 implementation with a focus on security and encompassing a privilege separated design.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Whilst it is aimed more closely at the simpler generic needs of OpenBSD users, it also includes some protocol security improvements while still being compatible with existing NTP servers.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The simpler code base sacrifices accuracy, deemed unnecessary in this use case.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A portable version is available in Linux package repositories.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTPsec is a fork of the reference implementation that has been systematically security-hardened.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The fork point was in June 2015 and was in response to a series of compromises in 2014.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The first production release shipped in October 2017.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Between removal of unsafe features, removal of support for obsolete hardware, and removal of support for obsolete Unix variants, NTPsec has been able to pare away 75% of the original codebase, making the remainder easier to audit.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A 2017 audit of the code showed eight security issues, including two that were not present in the original reference implementation, but NTPsec did not suffer from eight other issues that remained in the reference implementation.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] chrony is an independent NTP implementation mainly sponsored by Red Hat, who uses it as the default time program in their distributions.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Being written from scratch, chrony has a simpler codebase allowing for better security and lower resource consumption.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It does not however compromise on accuracy, instead syncing faster and better than the reference ntpd in many circumstances.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It is versatile enough for ordinary computers, which are unstable, go into sleep mode or have intermittent connection to the Internet.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It is also designed for virtual machines, a more unstable environment.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] chrony has been evaluated as "trustworthy", with only a few incidents.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It is able to achieve improved precision on LAN connections, using hardware timestamping on the network adapter.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Support for Network Time Security (NTS) was added on version 4.0. chrony is available under GNU General Public License version 2, was created by Richard Curnow in 1997 and is currently maintained by Miroslav Lichvar.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Support for NTS is available. ntpd-rs is part of the "Pendulum" project which also includes a Precision Time Protocol implementation "statime".
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Both projects are available under Apache and MIT software licenses.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] On the day of a leap second event, ntpd receives notification from either a configuration file, an attached reference clock, or a remote server.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Although the NTP clock is actually halted during the event, because of the requirement that time must appear to be strictly increasing, any processes that query the system time cause it to increase by a tiny amount, preserving the order of events.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] If a negative leap second should ever become necessary, it would be deleted with the sequence 23:59:58, 00:00:00, skipping 23:59:59.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] An alternative implementation, called leap smearing, consists in introducing the leap second incrementally during a period of 24 hours, from noon to noon in UTC time.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Because adjusting system time is generally a privileged operation, part or all of NTP code has to be run with some privileges in order to support its core functionality.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Only a few other security problems have been identified in the reference implementation of the NTP codebase, but those that appeared in 2009, such as arbitrary code execution and denial-of-service attacks, were cause for significant concern.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The protocol has been undergoing revision and review throughout its history.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The codebase for the reference implementation has undergone security audits from several sources for several years.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A stack buffer overflow exploit was discovered and patched in 2014.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Apple was concerned enough about this vulnerability that it used its auto-update capability for the first time.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] On systems using the reference implementation, which is running with root user's credential, this could allow unlimited access.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Some other implementations, such as OpenNTPD, have smaller code base and adopted other mitigation measures like privilege separation, are not subject to this flaw.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A 2017 security audit of three NTP implementations, conducted on behalf of the Linux Foundation's Core Infrastructure Initiative, suggested that both NTP and NTPsec were more problematic than chrony from a security standpoint.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP servers can be susceptible to man-in-the-middle attacks unless packets are cryptographically signed for authentication.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The computational overhead involved can make this impractical on busy servers, particularly during denial of service attacks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP message spoofing from a man-in-the-middle attack can be used to alter clocks on client computers and allow a number of attacks based on bypassing of cryptographic key expiration.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Some of the services affected by fake NTP messages identified are TLS, DNSSEC, various caching schemes (such as DNS cache), Border Gateway Protocol (BGP), Bitcoin and a number of persistent login schemes.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP has been used in distributed denial of service attacks.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] A small query is sent to an NTP server with the return IP address spoofed to be the target address.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Similar to the DNS amplification attack, the server responds with a much larger reply that allows an attacker to substantially increase the amount of data being sent to the target.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] To avoid participating in an attack, NTP server software can be upgraded or servers can be configured to ignore external queries.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP itself includes support for authenticating servers to clients.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTPv3 supports a symmetric key mode, which is not useful against MITM.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The public key system known as "autokey" in NTPv4 adapted from IPSec offers useful authentication, but is not practical for a busy server.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Autokey was also later found to suffer from several design flaws, with no correction published, save for a change in the message authentication code.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Microsoft also has an approach to authenticate NTPv3/SNTPv4 packets using a Windows domain identity, known as MS-SNTP.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This system is implemented in the reference ntpd and chrony, using samba for the domain connection.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Indicates the distance from the reference clock.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Maximum interval between successive messages, in log₂(seconds).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Signed log₂(seconds) of system clock precision (e.g., –18 ≈ 1 microsecond).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Total round-trip delay to the reference clock, in NTP short format.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Total dispersion to the reference clock, in NTP short format.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Identifies the specific server or reference clock; interpretation depends on Stratum.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Time when the system clock was last set or corrected, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Time at the client when the request departed, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The local time, in timestamp format, when the latest NTP message arrived.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Time at the server when the response left, in NTP timestamp format.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Unsigned integer designating an MD5 key shared by the client and server.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] MD5 hash covering the packet header and extension fields, used for authentication.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The 64-bit binary fixed-point timestamps used by NTP consist of a 32-bit part for seconds and a 32-bit part for fractional second, giving a time scale that rolls over every 232 seconds (136 years) and a theoretical resolution of 2−32 seconds (233 picoseconds).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Therefore, the first rollover occurs on February 7, 2036.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTPv4 introduces a 128-bit date format: 64 bits for the second and 64 bits for the fractional-second.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] However, the 128-bit format is never transmitted as the standard states that eras "cannot be produced by NTP directly, nor is there need to do so." The most-significant 32 bits of this format is the *Era Number* which would resolve rollover ambiguity in most cases.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] According to Mills, "The 64-bit value for the fraction is enough to resolve the amount of time it takes a photon to pass an electron at the speed of light.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] DHCPv4 allows clients to automatically obtain time sources as part of initial network configuration.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] It is commonly used in managed networks to ensure dynamic time synchronisation without manual configuration.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] RFC 2132 defines a dedicated DHCPv4 option for distributing NTP server addresses to clients.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The *Network Time Protocol Servers* option carries a list of IPv4 addresses identifying NTP servers available to the client.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Servers should be listed in order of preference, allowing the client to select the most appropriate source.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] While the Network Time Protocol (NTP) is responsible for synchronising system clocks to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), it does not distribute local time zone information.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Time zone configuration is handled separately at the operating system level.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This is especially useful for networks where devices are moving in and out, like cellular network.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Reduce the need to defined directly on device.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] These options are defined in RFC 4833 and apply to both DHCP for IPv4 (DHCPv4) and IPv6 (DHCPv6).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] Both options contain a variable-length string and are not null-terminated.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This option carries a time zone definition using the POSIX `TZ` environment variable format (as specified in IEEE 1003.1), except that the string must not begin with a colon (`:`).
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] For this option to be useful, the client must already have a local copy of the time zone database.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] If the client recognizes the provided name, it should prefer this option over the POSIX string.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] If the name is unknown, the option must be ignored.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] The semantics and string formats are identical to those used in DHCPv4; only the binary encoding differs due to protocol differences between DHCPv4 and DHCPv6.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] NTP distributes only absolute time (UTC) and does not include any information about local time zones or daylight saving rules.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] DHCP time zone options complement NTP by allowing clients to automatically configure their local time representation after their clocks have been synchronised.
[src:network-time-sync/network-time-protocol] This separation keeps NTP simple and avoids embedding region-specific political and legal time rules into the time synchronisation protocol.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The **Precision Time Protocol** (**PTP**) is a protocol for clock synchronization throughout a computer network with relatively high precision as compared to using the earlier developed Network Time Protocol (NTP) and therefore *potentially* higher accuracy depending on the configuration.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] In a local area network (LAN), accuracy can be sub-microsecond – making it suitable for measurement and control systems applications.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2008**, also known as PTP Version 2, is not backward compatible with the 2002 version.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 1588-2019** was published in November 2019 and includes backward-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 includes a *profile* concept defining PTP operating parameters and options.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Several profiles have been defined for applications including telecommunications, electric power distribution and audiovisual uses.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] **IEEE 802.1AS** is an adaptation of PTP, called gPTP, for use with Audio Video Bridging (AVB) and Time-Sensitive Networking (TSN).
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] According to John Eidson, who led the IEEE 1588-2002 standardization effort, "IEEE 1588 is designed to fill a niche not well served by either of the two dominant protocols, NTP and GPS.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588 is designed for local systems requiring accuracies beyond those attainable using NTP.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] PTP was originally defined in the IEEE 1588-2002 standard, officially titled *Standard for a Precision Clock Synchronization Protocol for Networked Measurement and Control Systems*, and published in 2002.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] In 2008, IEEE 1588-2008 was released as a revised standard; also known as PTP version 2 (PTPv2), it improves accuracy, precision and robustness but is not backward compatible with the original 2002 version.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2019 was published in November 2019, is informally known as *PTPv2.1* and includes backwards-compatible improvements to the 2008 publication.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The IEEE 1588 standards describe a hierarchical master–slave architecture for clock distribution consisting of one or more network segments and one or more clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] An *ordinary clock* is a device with a single network connection that is either the source of or the destination for a synchronization reference.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A source is called a *master* (alternately *timeTransmitter*), and a destination is called a *slave* (alternately *timeReceiver*).
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A *boundary clock* has multiple network connections and synchronizes one network segment to another.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A single, synchronization leader is selected, a.k.a. elected, for each network segment.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The root timing reference is called the *grandmaster*.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A relatively simple PTP architecture consists of ordinary clocks on a single-segment network with no boundary clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A grandmaster is elected and all other clocks synchronize to it.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2008 introduces a clock associated with network equipment used to convey PTP messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The *transparent clock* modifies PTP messages as they pass through the device.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Timestamps in the messages are corrected for time spent traversing the network equipment.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] This scheme improves distribution accuracy by compensating for delivery variability across the network.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] PTP typically uses the same epoch as Unix time (start of 1 January 1970).
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] While the Unix time is based on Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and is subject to leap seconds, PTP is based on International Atomic Time (TAI).
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The PTP grandmaster communicates the current offset between UTC and TAI, so that UTC can be computed from the received PTP time.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Synchronization and management of a PTP system is achieved through the exchange of messages across the communications medium.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] To this end, PTP uses the following message types.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Messages are categorized as *event* and *general* messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] *Event* messages are time-critical in that accuracy in transmission and receipt timestamp accuracy directly affects clock distribution accuracy.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] *Sync*, *Delay_Req*, *Pdelay_Req* and *Pdelay_resp* are *event* messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages are more conventional protocol data units in that the data in these messages is of importance to PTP, but their transmission and receipt timestamps are not.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] *Announce*, *Follow_Up*, *Delay_Resp*, *Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up*, *Management* and *Signaling* messages are members of the *general* message class.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] PTP messages may use the User Datagram Protocol over Internet Protocol (UDP/IP) for transport.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses only IPv4 transports, but this has been extended to include IPv6 in IEEE 1588-2008.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2002, all PTP messages are sent using multicast messaging, while IEEE 1588-2008 introduced an option for devices to negotiate unicast transmission on a port-by-port basis.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Multicast transmissions use IP multicast addressing, for which multicast group addresses are defined for IPv4 and IPv6 (see table).
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Time-critical *event* messages (Sync, Delay_req, Pdelay_Req and Pdelay_Resp) are sent to port number 319.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] *General* messages (Announce, Follow_Up, Delay_Resp, Pdelay_Resp_Follow_Up, management and signaling) use port number 320.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] In IEEE 1588-2008, encapsulation is also defined for DeviceNet, ControlNet and PROFINET.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A domain is an interacting set of clocks that synchronize to one another using PTP.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Clocks are assigned to a domain by virtue of the contents of the *Subdomain name* (IEEE 1588-2002) or the *domainNumber* (IEEE 1588-2008) fields in PTP messages they receive or generate.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Domains allow multiple clock distribution systems to share the same communications medium.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Class – each clock is a member of a given class, each class getting its own priority.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Priority 2 – final-defined priority, defining backup order in case the other criteria were not sufficient.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Smaller numeric values indicate higher priority.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Unique identifier – MAC address-based selection is used as a tiebreaker when all other properties are equal.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] IEEE 1588-2002 uses a selection algorithm based on similar properties.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Clock properties are advertised in IEEE 1588-2002 *Sync* messages and in IEEE 1588-2008 *Announce* messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The current leader transmits this information at regular interval.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A clock that considers itself a better leader will transmit this information in order to invoke a change of leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Once the current leader recognizes the better clock, the current leader stops transmitting *Sync* messages and associated clock properties (*Announce* messages in the case of IEEE 1588-2008) and the better clock takes over as leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The BMCA only considers the self-declared quality of clocks and does not take network link quality into consideration.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Via BMCA, PTP selects a source of time for an IEEE 1588 domain and for each network segment in the domain.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Clocks determine the offset between themselves and their leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Let the variable t represent physical time.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] where $s(t)$ represents the time measured by the follower clock at physical time t , and $m(t)$ represents the time measured by the leader clock at physical time t .
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The leader periodically broadcasts the current time as a message to the other clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2002 broadcasts are up to once per second.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Under IEEE 1588-2008, up to 10 per second are permitted.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Each broadcast begins at time $T_{1}$ with a *Sync* message sent by the leader to all the clocks in the domain.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] A clock receiving this message takes note of the local time $T_{1}'$ when this message is received.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The leader may subsequently send a multicast *Follow_Up* with accurate $T_{1}$ timestamp.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Not all leaders have the ability to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] It is only after the transmission is complete that they are able to retrieve an accurate timestamp for the *Sync* transmission from their network hardware.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with this limitation use the *Follow_Up* message to convey $T_{1}$ .
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Leaders with PTP capabilities built into their network hardware are able to present an accurate timestamp in the *Sync* message and do not need to send Follow_Up messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] In order to accurately synchronize to their leader, clocks must individually determine the network transit time of the *Sync* messages.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The transit time is determined indirectly by measuring round-trip time from each clock to its leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The clocks initiate an exchange with their leader designed to measure the transit time d .
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The exchange begins with a clock sending a *Delay_Req* message at time $T_{2}$ to the leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The leader receives and timestamps the *Delay_Req* at time $T_{2}'$ and responds with a *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The leader includes the timestamp $T_{2}'$ in the *Delay_Resp* message.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The clock now knows the offset ${\tilde {o}}$ during this transaction and can correct itself by this amount to bring it into agreement with their leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] One assumption is that this exchange of messages happens over a period of time so small that this offset can safely be considered constant over that period.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Another assumption is that the transit time of a message going from the leader to a follower is equal to the transit time of a message going from the follower to the leader.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] Finally, it is assumed that both the leader and follower can accurately measure the time they send or receive a message.
[src:network-time-sync/precision-time-protocol] The degree to which these assumptions hold true determines the accuracy of the clock at the follower device.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The aim of Synchronous Ethernet is to provide a synchronization signal to those network resources that may eventually require such a type of signal.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The Synchronous Ethernet signal transmitted over the Ethernet physical layer should be traceable to an external clock, ideally a master and unique clock for the whole network.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Applications include cellular networks, access technologies such as Ethernet passive optical network, and applications such as IPTV or VoIP.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Unlike time-division multiplexing networks, the Ethernet family of computer networks do not carry clock synchronization information.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Several means are defined to address this issue.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] IETF’s Network Time Protocol, IEEE's 1588-2008 Precision Time Protocol are some of them.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE architecture minimally requires replacement of the internal clock of the Ethernet card by a phase locked loop in order to feed the Ethernet PHY.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Extension of the synchronization network to consider Ethernet as a building block (ITU-T G.8261).
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] This enables Synchronous Ethernet network equipment to be connected to the same synchronization network as Synchronous Digital Hierarchy (SDH).
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronization for SDH can be transported over Ethernet and vice-versa.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] ITU-T G.8262 defines Synchronous Ethernet clocks compatible with SDH clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Synchronous Ethernet clocks, based on ITU-T G.813 clocks, are defined in terms of accuracy, noise transfer, holdover performance, noise tolerance and noise generation.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] These clocks are referred as Ethernet Equipment Slave clocks.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] While the IEEE 802.3 standard specifies Ethernet clocks to be within ±100 ppm.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] In addition, by timing the Ethernet clock, it is possible to achieve Primary Reference Clock (PRC) traceability at the interfaces.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] G.8262/Y.1362 is an ITU-T recommendation for Synchronous Ethernet that defines "timing characteristics of synchronous Ethernet equipment slave clock (EEC).
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] " It was first published in August 2007, amended in 2008 and 2010 and a new version published in 2010.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the Synchronization Status Message (SSM) provides traceability of synchronization signals and it is therefore required to extend the SSM functionality to Synchronous Ethernet to achieve full interoperability with SDH equipment.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] In SDH, the SSM message is carried in fixed locations within the SDH frame.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] However, in Ethernet there is no equivalent of a fixed frame.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The mechanisms needed to transport the SSM over Synchronous Ethernet are defined by the ITU-T in G.8264 in cooperation with IEEE.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] More specifically, the ESMC, defined by the ITU-T is based on the Organization Specific Slow Protocol (OSSP), currently specified in IEEE 802.3ay.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The ITU-T G.8264 defines a background or heart-beat message to provide a continuous indication of the clock quality level.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] However, event type messages with a new SSM quality level are generated immediately.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The ESMC protocol is composed of the standard Ethernet header for a slow protocol, an ITU-T specific header, a flag field and a type length value (TLV) structure.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The SSM encoded within the TLV is a four-bit field whose meaning is described in ITU-T G.781.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] A general requirement for SyncE was that any network element (NE) should have at least two reference clocks, and in addition, Ethernet interfaces must be able to generate their own synchronization signal in case they lose their external reference.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] If such is the case, it is said that the Ethernet node (EN) is in holdover.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronous signal must be filtered and regenerated by phase locked loop (PLL) at the Ethernet nodes since it degrades when passing through the network.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The synchronization and transport networks are partially mixed, since some NEs both transmit data and distribute clock signals to other NEs.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] SyncE networks do not usually have only one topology, but rather a combination of all of them.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Duplication and security involving more than one master clock, and the existence of some kind of synchronization management protocol, are important features of modern networks.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] The aim is to minimize the problems associated with signal transport, and to avoid depending on only one clock in case of failure.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] As a result, we get an extremely precise, redundant, and solid synchronization network.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Several type of networks can be used to transport the synchronous signal and could be combined indeed.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] Some of these networks are T1/E1, SONET/SDH and any rate, and SyncE.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] However *legacy Ethernet* is not suitable for transmitting synchronization signals.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] This is important because if the signal crosses a legacy Ethernet island then the synchronization is lost.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] *Line timing*: The NE obtains its clock by deriving it from one of the input signals.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] *Through timing*: Where the Tx outputs of one interface are synchronized with the Rx inputs of the opposite interface.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] *Internal timing*: In this mode, the internal clock of the EEC is used to synchronize outputs.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] It may be a temporary holdover stage after losing the synchronization signal, or it may be a simple line configuration where no other clock is available.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] A timing loop is in bad synchronization when the clock signal has closed itself, but there is no clock, either master or slave, that would autonomously generate a non-deficient clock signal.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] This situation can be caused by a fault affecting an NE in such a way that it has been left without a reference clock, and therefore it has chosen an alternative synchronization: a signal that has turned out to be the same signal, returning by another route.
[src:network-time-sync/synchronous-ethernet] A synchronization loop is a completely unstable situation that may provoke an immediate collapse of part of the network within the loop.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Today, **time synchronization** can occur between systems around the world through satellite navigation signals and other time and frequency transfer techniques.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Time-keeping and synchronization of clocks is a critical problem in long-distance ocean navigation.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Before radio navigation and satellite-based navigation, navigators required accurate time in conjunction with astronomical observations to determine how far east or west their vessel traveled.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] The invention of an accurate marine chronometer revolutionized marine navigation.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] By the end of the 19th century, important ports provided time signals in the form of a signal gun, flag, or dropping time ball so that mariners could check and correct their chronometers for error.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization was important in the operation of 19th-century railways, these being the first major means of transport fast enough for differences in local mean time between nearby towns to be noticeable.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Each line handled the problem by synchronizing all its stations to headquarters as a standard railway time.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In some territories, companies shared a single railroad track and needed to avoid collisions.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] The need for strict timekeeping led the companies to settle on one standard, and civil authorities eventually abandoned local mean time in favor of railway time.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In electrical engineering terms, for digital logic and data transfer, a synchronous circuit requires a clock signal.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] A clock signal simply signals the start or end of some time period, often measured in microseconds or nanoseconds, that has an arbitrary relationship to any other system of measurement of the passage of minutes, hours, and days.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In a different sense, electronic systems are sometimes synchronized to make events at points far apart appear simultaneous or near-simultaneous from a certain perspective.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Timekeeping technologies such as the GPS satellites and Network Time Protocol (NTP) provide real-time access to a close approximation to the UTC timescale and are used for many terrestrial synchronization applications of this kind.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In computer science (especially parallel computing), synchronization is the coordination of simultaneous threads or processes to complete a task with correct runtime order and no unexpected race conditions; see synchronization (computer science) for details.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization of multiple interacting dynamical systems can occur when the systems are autonomous oscillators.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Poincaré phase oscillators are model systems that can interact and partially synchronize within random or regular networks.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In the case of global synchronization of phase oscillators, an abrupt transition from unsynchronized to full synchronization takes place when the coupling strength exceeds a critical threshold.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] This is known as the Kuramoto model phase transition.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization is an emergent property that occurs in a broad range of dynamical systems, including neural signaling, the beating of the heart and the synchronization of fire-fly light waves.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] A unified approach that quantifies synchronization in chaotic systems can be derived from the statistical analysis of measured data.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Amplitude, frequency, and phase synchronization, as forms of coupling and interaction, underlie biological and physiological network mechanisms through which global states, functions and behaviors emerge at the system and organism level.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In cognitive neuroscience, (stimulus-dependent) (phase-)synchronous oscillations of neuron populations serve to solve the general binding problem.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] According to the so-called Binding-By-Synchrony (BBS) Hypothesis a precise temporal correlation between the impulses of neurons ("cross-correlation analysis") and thus a stimulus-dependent temporal synchronization of the coherent activity of subpopulations of neurons emerges.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Moreover, this synchronization mechanism circumvents the *superposition problem* by more effectively identifying the signature of synchronous neuronal signals as belonging together for subsequent (sub-)cortical information processing areas.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] There is a concept that the synchronization of biochemical reactions determines biological homeostasis.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] According to this theory, all reactions occurring in a living cell are synchronized in terms of quantities and timescales to maintain biological network functional.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization of movement is defined as similar movements between two or more people who are temporally aligned.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] This is different from mimicry, which occurs after a short delay.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Line dance and military step are examples.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Muscular bonding is the idea that moving in time evokes particular emotions.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] This sparked some of the first research into movement synchronization and its effects on human emotion.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In groups, synchronization of movement has been shown to increase conformity, cooperation and trust.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In dyads, groups of two people, synchronization has been demonstrated to increase affiliation, self-esteem, compassion and altruistic behaviour and increase rapport.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] During arguments, synchrony between the arguing pair has been noted to decrease; however, it is not clear whether this is due to the change in emotion or other factors.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] There is evidence to show that movement synchronization requires other people to cause its beneficial effects, as the effect on affiliation does not occur when one of the dyad is synchronizing their movements to something outside the dyad.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] This is known as interpersonal synchrony.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] The true effect of synchrony in these studies has been disputed.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Research in this area detailing the positive effects of synchrony has attributed this to synchrony alone; however, many of the experiments incorporate a shared intention to achieve synchrony.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Indeed, the Reinforcement of Cooperation Model suggests that perception of synchrony leads to reinforcement that cooperation is occurring, which leads to the pro-social effects of synchrony.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] More research is required to separate the effect of intentionality from the beneficial effect of synchrony.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization is important in digital telephony, video and digital audio where streams of sampled data are manipulated.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronization of image and sound was an important technical problem in sound film.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] More sophisticated film, video, and audio applications use time code to synchronize audio and video.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In movie and television production, it is necessary to synchronize video frames from multiple cameras.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In addition to enabling basic editing, synchronization can also be used for 3D reconstruction.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] In electric power systems, alternator synchronization is required when multiple generators are connected to an electrical grid.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Arbiters are needed in digital electronic systems such as microprocessors to deal with asynchronous inputs.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] There are also electronic digital circuits called *synchronizers* that attempt to perform arbitration in one clock cycle.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Synchronizers, unlike arbiters, are prone to failure.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Encryption systems usually require some synchronization mechanism to ensure that the receiving cipher is decoding the right bits at the right time.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Automotive transmissions contain synchronizers that bring the toothed rotating parts (gears and splined shaft) to the same rotational velocity before engaging the teeth.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Flash synchronization synchronizes the flash with the shutter.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Some systems may be only approximately synchronized, or plesiochronous.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] Some applications require that relative offsets between events be determined.
[src:network-time-sync/time-synchronization] For others, only the order of the event is important.
